WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:10.000
My name is Laura DiCicco and I work at the United States Geological Survey.

00:00:10.000 --> 00:00:15.000
Today I'll be talking about a package I developed and maintained for the USGS called Data Retrieval.

00:00:15.000 --> 00:00:19.000
What is USGS? It's a United States federal government agency.

00:00:19.000 --> 00:00:24.000
Its mission is to monitor, analyze, and predict current and evolving Earth system interactions

00:00:24.000 --> 00:00:27.000
and deliver actionable information to decision makers.

00:00:27.000 --> 00:00:36.000
The USGS has scientists that study volcanoes, earthquakes, ecosystems, and has a long history of making cool maps.

00:00:36.000 --> 00:00:42.000
But what I'm here to tell you about today is the story of USGS water data and how you can get that into R.

00:00:42.000 --> 00:00:46.000
There's a huge variety of data that the USGS collects concerning water.

00:00:46.000 --> 00:00:50.000
Surface water data includes things like gauge height and discharge.

00:00:50.000 --> 00:00:54.000
Scientists use this data to study how water levels are changing over time,

00:00:54.000 --> 00:00:58.000
monitor current river conditions, and predict flooding.

00:00:58.000 --> 00:01:01.000
The USGS also studies groundwater data.

00:01:01.000 --> 00:01:06.000
This includes information about springs and wells that indicate aquifer conditions.

00:01:06.000 --> 00:01:12.000
We can use this data to understand how human activities and climate change affects the supply of groundwater.

00:01:12.000 --> 00:01:17.000
There are estimates for how much water is used in the United States and generally what that water is used for.

00:01:17.000 --> 00:01:21.000
Water use data might include things like the volume of water used for irrigation

00:01:21.000 --> 00:01:25.000
or the amount of water in a public water supply system.

00:01:25.000 --> 00:01:31.000
Water quality data includes physical data like temperature, chemical data, and biological data.

00:01:31.000 --> 00:01:36.000
For example, with water quality data we can study the effects of road salt on streams or lakes.

00:01:36.000 --> 00:01:44.000
Or maybe we're looking at chemicals of emerging concern such as pesticides, microplastics, or PFAS.

00:01:44.000 --> 00:01:50.000
I started at the USGS about 13 years ago and not too long after that I was asked to learn R.

00:01:50.000 --> 00:01:55.000
It was around then that the USGS was deciding to move our support officially from SAS to R.

00:01:55.000 --> 00:01:59.000
There were some scientists already using R but it wasn't very widespread.

00:01:59.000 --> 00:02:01.000
For the most part Excel was king.

00:02:01.000 --> 00:02:07.000
Keep in mind RStudio at that time hadn't been around much and alternative IDEs were not very user friendly.

00:02:07.000 --> 00:02:12.000
One thing that became obvious right away that it was very difficult to get our USGS water data into R.

00:02:12.000 --> 00:02:16.000
This data bottleneck seemed like the first big hurdle that would need to be overcome

00:02:16.000 --> 00:02:20.000
to convince people to invest in the time to learn R.

00:02:20.000 --> 00:02:25.000
I'd been hired into a smaller group within the USGS that had a great mix of scientists and software developers.

00:02:25.000 --> 00:02:30.000
This meant that from the very beginning of my R development I was being taught about version control,

00:02:30.000 --> 00:02:35.000
unit testing, project management, and other software management development best practices.

00:02:35.000 --> 00:02:41.000
And so on one fateful day in November 2012 I pushed up a set of code to GitHub.

00:02:41.000 --> 00:02:44.000
There were some hurdles we had to jump through to work in the open

00:02:44.000 --> 00:02:51.000
but I've been lucky to have had extremely supportive supervisors who advocate for open source development.

00:02:51.000 --> 00:02:56.000
It did not take long to start seeing some immediate benefits of creating a package to help users get their data.

00:02:56.000 --> 00:03:03.000
Standardizing the data retrieval phase of code made collaborating easier and jumping into analyzing the data quicker.

00:03:03.000 --> 00:03:08.000
More emphasis was being placed on reproducible science and data retrieval made that a little easier.

00:03:08.000 --> 00:03:10.000
Community engagement flourished.

00:03:10.000 --> 00:03:17.000
We introduced still active GitHub and GitLab organizations, social media, blogging, and various training sessions.

00:03:17.000 --> 00:03:21.000
Data retrieval has been downloaded over 186,000 times.

00:03:21.000 --> 00:03:24.000
For a pretty niche package that's good.

00:03:24.000 --> 00:03:28.000
Data retrieval users are fantastic at finding problems with our data and services

00:03:28.000 --> 00:03:32.000
and honestly they're also really great at helping fix those problems.

00:03:32.000 --> 00:03:36.000
There have been many USGS R packages developed over the years.

00:03:36.000 --> 00:03:43.000
We recently got a Posit Connect license and it's been a joy to watch it flourish with Shiny apps, Quarto reports, and Plumber APIs.

00:03:43.000 --> 00:03:47.000
As a main point of contact for data retrieval I've been contacted by users in many different fields

00:03:47.000 --> 00:03:50.000
and it's a real highlight of my career.

00:03:50.000 --> 00:03:53.000
I wanted to share some examples of all the cool projects that use data retrieval

00:03:53.000 --> 00:03:56.000
but this talk's way too short and there are way too many to pick from.

00:03:56.000 --> 00:04:01.000
Here's a small list of examples of topics that I've known that use data retrieval extensively.

00:04:01.000 --> 00:04:07.000
There's also been many cool data visualizations that use data retrieval in their creation process.

00:04:07.000 --> 00:04:10.000
One recently came out from the New York Times about groundwater.

00:04:10.000 --> 00:04:15.000
Within the USGS we have a group that creates stunning water-related visualizations.

00:04:15.000 --> 00:04:18.000
I'd encourage you all to check out the USGS VisLab group.

00:04:18.000 --> 00:04:23.000
As our studio pivoted to Posit to connect with more diverse users

00:04:23.000 --> 00:04:28.000
so did the USGS realize we really needed a similar product for Python.

00:04:28.000 --> 00:04:35.000
So this last year we officially added support for both a Python and Julia data retrieval package.

00:04:35.000 --> 00:04:40.000
I hope what you got from this talk was that making a relatively small investment in an R package

00:04:40.000 --> 00:04:43.000
is a great way to foster a thriving R community.

00:04:43.000 --> 00:04:47.000
For the USGS that's meant people have been able to get their data analysis faster

00:04:47.000 --> 00:04:50.000
with reproducible transparent data pipelines.

00:04:50.000 --> 00:04:55.000
In our current era of rapid hydrologic change this is critical for our USGS mission.

00:04:55.000 --> 00:04:58.000
If you're interested in checking out the data retrieval package

00:04:58.000 --> 00:05:00.000
here's some links that should help you get started.

00:05:00.000 --> 00:05:01.000
Thank you.

00:05:01.000 --> 00:05:06.000
Applause

